    "label_text": "In 1935, Herbert Bayer depicted a man with a giant eye for a head attending an exhibition. Flat planes confront the man from diverse angles, canted from the walls, ceiling, and floor. Bayer\u2019s drawing is based on an exhibition he created with former Bauhaus compatriots, L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Moholy-Nagy and Walter Gropius, in 1930. The exhibition, Section Allemande (German Section), featured photographs of modern architecture installed at various angles. In Bayer\u2019s poster for the exhibition, a tiny human figure stands dwarfed beneath a huge white sphere. The sphere\u2014casting a shadow on a vast white plane resembling a movie screen\u2014symbolizes the engulfing, larger-thanlife optical experience of modernity.",
